content: I really like the calendar. Question: why doesn't it show days like Valentine's day, Good Friday, Easter? I have holidays in US marked but those days won't show up. That's a reason I can't put 5 stars.

Complaints about the new release are overblown.  However, to the developer: Think about your paying customers. People who paid for this app have grown used to the interface, and to their customizations. When it is changed without warning, they lose the smooth flow of the software; it becomes an impediment, and an aggravation. Not everybody wants to spend a half hour picking through the changes and re-customizing everything. When your app becomes an irritant instead of a familiar, smooth workflow, users are going to get upset.  Replying to complaints with surly criticism, telling users they're wrong, only further irritates them. The release process was done badly, and snarky replies to comments don't help. People who pay money for a product expect the product to behave consistently.  If you make a major change to the UI, the old interface should remain available. The option is often called "Classic" or some such. That way, users can work with the look-and-feel they're used to, but can also switch to the new look in order to get familiar with it. A little courtesy, and giving some thought to your users, will go a long way toward maintaining customer loyalty.
replyContent:
Thanks for the feedback.
Offering a classic interface for a short while is usually done by companies that charge you for every update. There was really not that much of a UI change here except for things that were really broken (menu) or dated (agenda), everything else is rather minor or configurable. The main problem is with bad user data...

Admittedly, over the years, through PC failures and Window upgrades, I got frustrated when I encountered issues with the calendar and could not reach a live person by phone.  However, 6 years later, this calendar application has worked with every new Windows upgrade and every new PC and android phone, up to today -- Samsung 9 Plus and Windows 10.  Once the USB settings are made in accord with the simple instructions, my calendar is up and running.  I thought I'd get a prettier calendar or more features by going with a cloud-based calendar sync program elsewhere.  But the cloud is fraught with potential security issues and when I attempted to rely on USB I encountered errors everyday.  I was thankful to have been able to switch back to Android Sync where I have had a reliable calendar for all of my 9,000+ appointments and reliable 500+ contacts for 6 years.

This app brings with it an invaluable tool to managing your time! This is one of the best calendar-based application on the market! I started out using the free version in 2015 and enjoyed how the app creates a user-friendly and accessible calendar. What won me over was the ability to create events with specific times, durations, locations, attendees, etc.. I later transitioned over to the premium version that includes the task app (highly recommend) which works well in conjunction with the Calendar app. With both of these apps helping to organize and coordinate my payments, finances, social time, studying, working, and time with family, I have been a fan of aCalendar ever since!  The calendar app excels at offering variety  with how the time intervals for notifications (6,12,18 hour, etc.) and repeat events  (daily, bi-weekly, etc.) are set. It works effectively at being very customizable with both the color palette on the Task and Calendar app. Likewise, the offline performance and cross synchronization between calendars and devices are a major bonus. This app is excellent for anyone needing to effectively organize their time and visually map out their schedule.   I would recommend in the Tasks app giving each "tasks entered" the option for a reminder alarm (similar to how the Calendar app offers this for when you are creating events). In the premium Calendar app, adding a wider color palette (more than 12 colors) in the "add event" menu would offer more customization and  improve on what it greatly offers.  Please keep up the great work with this Calendar app; you have a fan for the foreseeable future!

There's no way to link tasks to specific days . It just Packs all of the tasks for the entire month into one long list. l wanted this app to replace my Franklin planner. The  calendar portion is great, but unfortunately for me, I  have a lot of tasks that need to be done on Specific days, but are not at any particular scheduled time. This app is terrible for managing tasks. Oh, and why should I have to sign into Google just to add tasks? RESPONSE TO DEVELOPER: yes, I missed the 'due date' option in the tasks section. With that, the app becomes functional for my needs. But, the point I  want to impress on prospective users, is that this app strongly favors and is geared towards those who schedule lots of appointments. If your primary use is tasks, you are likely to be disappointed. On most of my days, I have many tasks for the day, crammed into a small corner of the screen, while 80% of the screen (the hour by hour appointment portion) remains blank. I have to click on the task to read the full title. Then, when I go to the task list page, I see all past, present and future tasks in one giant long list. A default 'task view' option would improve the app greatly. I'll add 1 star.

A few features could still be improved: * Nice if widget could list unscheduled tasks at top * For calendar's week layout, I'd find it more intuitive if I could select horizontal matrix when in landscape and vertical matrix when in portrait. * Syncing isn't as responsive as I'd like. I often use different devices and I appreciate that it would use up too much battery/bandwidth to poll changes all the time, but would be nice if every change on the device triggered a sync. When in tasks, does requesting an explicit sync also sync calendar, and vice versa? I'm not sure. * In day view, long press on a time allow to create a task whereas long press on the space where tasks show only allows to create an all-day event, not a task. I think it'd be more intuitive if you could create a task from where they are displayed. * When selecting multiple tasks, the only action that one can do in bulk is to delete them. I often want to reschedule several tasks at the same time. It would be nice to select them all and then reschedule them to another day.
replyContent: Sync is separate for calendar and tasks. Calendar sync is handled by the cloud service's (e.g. Google Calendar) sync adapter and should operate in PUSH mode. Tasks should also push local changes. The idea of directly creating a new all-day event in that area is to save 1 tap - asking the user what to do there would defy that purpose.

replyContent: No, this is required to do anything while the phone is sleeping (e.g. bringing up an alarm) which requires querying a database and thus must be done in a service. Without the wake lock (hence the permission) the phone might go back to sleep before the service is running. Once the action is finished the wake lock is removed.
